C = extension(A,A + reflect(A,B)*(T),T,T + dir(110));
P = foot(A,C,T);

draw(Circle(O,9));
draw(A--B--T--cycle);
draw(A--P--C);

label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, SE);
label("$C$", C, NE);
label("$O$", O, S);
label("$P$", P, S);
label("$T$", T, NW);
[/asy]

Since $\overline{CT}$ is tangent to $\omega$, $\angle CTO = 90^\circ$. Also, $\angle BTO = 90^\circ$ since $\overline{AB}$ is a diameter. Therefore, quadrilateral $BTOA$ is cyclic. 

By Power of a Point on $\overline{CT}$, we have $CP \cdot CT = CA \cdot CB = (18 + AC) \cdot 18$. 

Since $AP \perp CT$, we have $CP = \sqrt{CT^2 - AP^2}$. 

By Pythagoras on right triangle $ABP$, we have $AP = \sqrt{AB^2 - BP^2} = \sqrt{18^2 - BP^2}$. 

Substituting these into our equation, we have $\sqrt{CT^2 - (18^2 - BP^2)} \cdot CT = (18 + AC) \cdot 18$. Squaring both sides, we get 

\[(CT^2 - (18^2 - BP^2)) \cdot CT^2 = (18 + AC)^2 \cdot 18^2.\]Expanding, we have $CT^4 - 18^2 CT^2 + BP^2 CT^2 = (18 + AC)^2 \cdot 18^2$. 

Since $\angle CTO = 90^\circ$, by Pythagoras on right triangle $CTO$, we have $CT^2 = CO^2 + OT^2 = 18^2 + 9^2 = 405$. 

Substituting this value of $CT^2$, we have $405^2 - 18^2 \cdot 405 + BP^2 \cdot 405 = (18 + AC)^2 \cdot 18^2$. 

Since $AC > 0$, the maximum value of $BP^2$ occurs when $AC$ is minimized. This occurs when $C$ is as close to $A$ as possible. 

When $C$ is as close to $A$ as possible, $\angle CTA$ is as close to $180^\circ$ as possible. 

Therefore, $m^2 = \dfrac{(18 + AC)^2 \cdot 18^2 - 405^2 + 18^2 \cdot 405}{405} = \dfrac{(18 + AC)^2 \cdot 18^2}{405}$. 

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $CTA$, we have 

\[CT^2 = CA^2 + AT^2 - 2 \cdot CA \cdot AT \cdot \cos \angle CTA.\]Since $\cos \angle CTA \approx -1$, we have $405 \approx CA^2 + 9^2 + 2 \cdot CA \cdot 9$. 

Solving for $CA$, we find $CA \approx 14$. 

Substituting, we have $m^2 \approx \dfrac{(18 + 14)^2 \cdot 18^2}{405} \approx 1600$. 

